The daemon configuration.

The daemon reads a configuration file under slash e-t-c slash docker at startup. The file is optional, so with nothing there the defaults apply, and the full schema is huge. What matters is the handful of settings you actually touch in practice.

A typical configuration moves the data directory to a dedicated disk so docker does not fill the operating-system root partition. It sets the storage driver explicitly to overlay-two. It sets the logging driver with a maximum size and file count, which you should basically always do, because without it the default logs grow until they fill the disk. It can register alternative runtimes and pick a default among them. It can list registry mirrors to consult first on pulls, which is the cache from notebook seven. It can enable user-namespace remapping and no-new-privileges from notebook eight. It can turn off the userland network proxy in favour of pure firewall rules. It can enable live-restore, which lets the daemon restart without killing running containers, which is handy during daemon upgrades. It can set the address pools that user-defined networks allocate from, so they do not clash with your corporate subnets. And it can expose metrics about docker itself for monitoring.

After editing, you reload the daemon to pick up the change. A plain reload suffices for some settings, but a few, like the storage driver, the data directory, and user-namespace remapping, require a full restart. Whatever you change, the daemon's reported configuration always reflects what is actually loaded, so verifying there after a restart is the way to confirm your change took effect rather than assuming it did.
